<subsection xml:id="subsec-proportional-parts">
    <title>Proportional Parts</title>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
            Masomo School has a total of <m>500</m> Mathematics textbooks, <m>100</m> storybooks, and <m>300</m> Science textbooks.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        Find the ratio of Mathematics textbooks to storybooks to Science textbooks.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Express each type of book as a fraction of the total number of books in the school.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        Explain the steps you used to obtain these fractions.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The textbooks are to be shared among <m>90</m> students in the ratio <m>5:1:3</m> for Mathematics, storybooks, and Science respectively. Work out how many books of each type each student would get.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with your fellow learners.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition xml:id="def-proportions">
        <statement>
            <p>
            <m>\textbf{Proportion}</m> is an equation in which two ratios are set equal to each other.
            For example, if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are in the same ratio as <m>c</m> and <m>d</m>, we can write this as: 
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>a:b = c:d</me>. This means that the fraction <m>\frac{a}{b}</m> is equal to the fraction <m>\frac{c}{d}</m>.

            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <alert>Key Takeaway</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        If an amount <m>m</m> is to be divided in the ratio  <m>a:b:c</m>,
        then the proportional parts will be divided as follows:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker="i)">
            <li>
                <p>
                   <m>a</m> will get <m>\frac{a}{a+b+c} \times m</m> 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                     <m>b</m> will get <m>\frac{b}{a+b+c} \times m</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>c</m> will get <m>\frac{c}{a+b+c} \times m</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A basket of fruits contains mangoes, oranges, and bananas in the ratio of <m>3:2:5</m>. 
               If the basket has a total of <m>100</m> fruits, find the number of each type of fruit.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the number of each type of fruit, we first add the parts in the ratio:
                <m>3 + 2 + 5 = 10</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow> \text{Number of mangoes} =\amp  \frac{3}{10} \times \text{number of fruits}. </mrow> 
                  <mrow> =\amp \frac{3}{10} \times 100 </mrow>
                  <mrow> =\amp 30 </mrow>
                  <mrow> \text{Number of oranges} =\amp  \frac{2}{10} \times \text{number of fruits}. </mrow> 
                  <mrow> =\amp \frac{2}{10} \times 100 </mrow>
                  <mrow> =\amp 20 </mrow>
                  <mrow> \text{Number of bananas} =\amp  \frac{5}{10} \times \text{number of fruits}. </mrow> 
                  <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{10} \times 100 </mrow>
                  <mrow> =\amp 50 </mrow>
                </md>
                 
            </p>
        </solution>  
    </example>    
    <example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Find the value of <m>z</m> in the proportion <m>12 : z = 4 : 5</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Step 1: Recall that if <m>a:b = c:d</m>, it can be written as a fraction: 
            <m>\frac{a}{b} = \frac{c}{d}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            So, <me>\frac{12}{z} = \frac{4}{5}</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Step 2: Cross-multiply to eliminate the fractions:
            <m>12 \times 5 = 4 \times z</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Step 3: Simplify the equation:
            <m>60 = 4z</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Step 4: Divide both sides by <m>4</m>:
            <m>z = \frac{60}{4} = 15</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the value of <m>z</m> is <m>15</m>.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
 
</subsection>